data.title: Justin Timberlake's voting selfie being 'reviewed' by authorities
data.meta_description: Justin Timberlake apparently broke Tennessee law on Monday by taking a selfie while voting, which has been outlawed in the state since 2015.
data.text:
var _ndnq = _ndnq || []; _ndnq.push([’embed’]);

Justin Timberlake took a selfie Monday while voting early in his hometown of Memphis, Tennessee.

Justin Timberlake broke the law.

Taking pictures at polling places is against the law in a number of states, including Tennessee, according to Us Weekly.

The 35-year-old posted a picture of himself casting his ballot to social media, with the caption “Hey! You! Yeah, YOU! I just flew from LA to Memphis to #rockthevote.,” He also wrote “There could be early voting in your town too. If not, November 8th! Choose to have a voice! If you don’t, then we can’t HEAR YOU! Get out and VOTE! #exerciseyourrighttovote.”

He means well. Then again, is there a celebrity alive who can resist doing anything of note without having to take their own picture?

The Shelby County District Attorney’s Office communications director Vince Higgins told Us Weekly the department “was made aware of a possible violation of election law. The matter is under review by the D.A.’s office.” Offenders could face a 30-day jail sentence and a fine of $50.

He could probably handle the fine.

The law, which came into being in May 2015, says that voters may use their phones at polling stations for “informational purposes to assist the voter in making election decisions.” But taking photos or videos is a no-no.

It’s not clear who JT voted for. but his wife, Jessica Biel, attended a fundraiser for Hillary Clinton in August.
